Army of the Apocalypse	Whirlwind rebel host led by Sha'ik, aggregating desert tribes, defected Malazan units, and fanatics under commanders such as Korbolo Dom and Leoman of the Flails.
Barghast	The Barghast are a nomadic warrior society of non-human origin, physically imposing with features reminiscent of their Imass ancestors. Their culture is organized into rival clans, each with a rich history recorded in intricate tattoos. Guided by shamans who commune with ancestral spirits, they are known for their martial prowess and sexually free customs. A core tenet of their existence is a holy war promised by their ancestor-gods. <br><br><i>"Those boys will fight anyone, anywhere."</i><br>
Brethen	Tribal people of northern Genabackis.
Bright Knot	Northern tribal people.
Daru	The Daru are the inhabitants of Darujhistan, the 'City of Blue Fire' on Genabackis. Renowned for their ingenuity, they have harnessed natural gas for lighting and industry. Their city is an oligarchy governed by a council of nobles, and the Daru people are known for their resilience and independent spirit, thriving in a metropolis of political intrigue and ancient secrets.
Eleint	Ancient and powerful race of pure dragons originating from the Elder Warren of Starvald Demelain. They are considered fragments of the goddess T'iam, bound by shared histories and bloodlines, but driven by rage due to their splintered natures. Eleint were enormous, scaled, reptilian monstrosities with long, sinewy necks, webbed wings, terrible fanged jaws, and deadly taloned hands. They possessed more than one heart. Their eyes had vertical pupils, like a goat.
Fildasz	Northern tribal people.
Forkrul Assail	The Forkrul Assail are an extinct mythical people, one of the Four Founding Races of the Malazan world. Known for their pursuit of absolute justice and order, they wielded immense power through their voices and the Hold of Ahkrast Korvalain.
Gadrobi	Indigenous people of central Genabackis.
Gandaru	The Gandaru are a tribal people from the Lamatath Plain, closely related to the Kindaru. They are a near-extinct people, characterized by their sloped brows, tawny-hued eyes, and a wary, animal-like demeanor. Their features are a unique blend of human and animal, suggesting an alternate version of humanity. With dark skin and broad, expressive mouths, the Gandaru are a fleeting presence in the world.
Ganrel	Tribal people of northern Genabackis.
Genabarii	The Genabarii are a cultural group and language found in northwest Genabackis. The city of Genabaris serves as a major settlement for this people.
Jaghut	The Jaghut are an extinct mythical people, one of the Four Founding Races of the Malazan world. Solitary by nature and masters of ice magic through Omtose Phellack, they were hunted nearly to extinction by the T'lan Imass in an eternal war.
Jheck	The Jheck are a mysterious and dangerous people, often described as D'ivers wolves. They are a type of shapeshifter, capable of transforming into multiple wolves. Their exact origins are debated, with some theories suggesting they are remnants of an ancient soletaken ritual in the land of Lether. The Jheck are a formidable and predatory force, known for their pack-like behavior and ferocity in battle.
Jhinan	Tribal people of northern Genabackis.
Kindaru	The Kindaru are a tribal people from the Lamatath Plain and are known to be the cousins of the Gandaru. Like their relatives, they are a reclusive and mysterious group, with a deep connection to their ancestral lands. While little is known about their specific customs, their shared ancestry with the Gandaru suggests a similar blend of human and ancient, animal-like traits, making them a unique and enigmatic presence in the Malazan world.
Korvalahrai|Korvalah	The Korvalahrai were a race of demon seafarers from the warren of Aral Gamelon. They spoke with the voices of children.
K'chain Che'Malle	The K'chain Che'Malle are an extinct mythical people, one of the Four Founding Races of the Malazan world. These reptilian beings once ruled vast territories and possessed advanced technology and devastating martial prowess before their civilization collapsed.
Moranth	A highly regimented people who were centred in the Cloud Forest of Genabackis. Their culture was largely closed off from outsiders, who found their ways something of a mystery.
Rhivi	The Rhivi are a nomadic people who dwell on the central plains of Genabackis, following the great herds in a seasonal cycle. They are a small, brown-skinned people who live in harmony with the land, building no permanent structures. Though not a warlike people, they were forced to ally with Caladan Brood against the Malazan Empire. Their culture is rich with unique customs, including a distinctive marriage ritual involving braided grass, and they revere a pantheon of nature spirits.
Red Blades	Fanatical Seven Cities cavalry loyal to the Empire; originally rebels, later reinstated as Imperial irregulars hunting Sha'ik’s agents such as Kalam.
Saemdhi	The Saemdhi are an indigenous people of the northern tundra, believed to be closely related to the pre-Ritual Imass. For generations, they were held captive as part of a Jaghut experiment, imprisoned behind a vast wall of ice. With the melting of their prison, the Saemdhi have been released into a world that has long forgotten them, carrying with them the legacy of their ancient origins and their harrowing ordeal.
Seguleh	The Seguleh are a reclusive and enigmatic people from an island south of Morn, feared and respected for their martial prowess. Their society is a strict martial hierarchy, where rank is everything, displayed through markings on their masks. They are a warrior caste, and their entire culture revolves around combat and the pursuit of individual standing within their rigid system. The name 'Seguleh' is an old word for 'The Anvil,' hinting at a possible origin as a remnant of a forgotten empire's army.
Semk	A Seven Cities tribe centered in the Karas Hills and Steppes who had an avowed hatred of all who were not Semk. They had a reputation as fierce warriors who kept captive enemies alive so that they could torture them, and during battle they covered themselves in ash and fought in a wild, undisciplined manner. Their tribal god was an ancient and vicious Ascendant who granted the tribe's sorcerers their powers. Members of the South Clan were known to cover their bodies in tattoos.
Sinbarl	Tribal people of the Lamatath Plain.
Tanno	A Seven Cities tribe whose holy men were known as Spiritwalkers. Their magic was manifested through songs of power rather than conventional sorcery. Members of the tribe were largely short and bow-legged, and the Tanno cult claimed direct descent from the cult of the Nameless Ones. Karakarang was their Holy City. The Spiritwalkers maintained that their power was based on the original patterns created by their predecessors' rituals, patterns said to criss-cross the entire subcontinent of Seven Cities to the present day.
Tapuharal	A Seven Cities term originating from the Bisbrha and Debrahl languages, denoting a seller of cooked goat meat—a specialized variant of the broader term 'Tapu' for food-hawker. These mobile vendors operated in urban settings, selling roasted meats and fruits prepared on skewers approximately four feet in length, serving as common commercial fixtures in Seven Cities' markets providing affordable sustenance to residents and travelers.
Skathandi	The Skathandi are a tribal people from the Lamatath Plain, with a kingdom that was once a notable power in the region. Their history is marked by tragedy, including the crucifixion of their king and their involvement in the Pannion War. The Skathandi are a people with a deep and complex history, their legacy intertwined with the turbulent events of the Malazan world. Their culture and traditions are not widely known, adding to their enigmatic presence.
Teblor	The Teblor are a proud and isolated offshoot of the Thelomen Toblakai, a race of giants. Deliberately sheltered from the outside world, they have developed a seemingly primitive culture, having lost much of their ancestral knowledge. They are significantly larger and stronger than humans, with a fierce warrior tradition. The term 'Teblor' is often used to refer specifically to the tribes from which the famed warrior Karsa Orlong hails, and while related to the broader Toblakai, they are a distinct and formidable people in their own right.
Thelomen Tartheno Toblakai	The Thelomen Tartheno Toblakai are an intelligent humanoid race descended from the Thel Akai, said to be the blessed children of the Great Mother. Once a unified people, they scattered across the world long ago, with isolated tribes living unaware of their distant relatives on different continents. These beings are notably taller and more robust than humans, with distinctive broad, flat faces and pure-blooded individuals typically exceeding seven feet in height. They possess four lungs rather than two, and can interbreed with humans to produce viable offspring. Once great civilizations with cities and written knowledge, most contemporary populations had declined to tribal societies.
T'lan Imass|Imass	The T'lan Imass, also known as the Silent Host, are an undead Elder Race, one of the four Founding Races of the Malazan world. They were mortal Imass who underwent the Ritual of Tellann, which granted them immortality in exchange for their flesh, leaving them as sentient, mummified corpses. They are bound by an eternal war against the Jaghut. Their shamans are known as Bonecasters, and they possess the ability to travel great distances by turning to dust and riding the winds.
Tiste Andii	The Tiste Andii were a non-human Elder Race, Children of Darkness and first of Mother Dark's children, dwellers of the land before light and sometimes called the Souls of Starless Night; immortal and led by Archmage Anomander Rake, they once lived in Kurald Galain around their first city Kharkanas, worshipping Mother Dark until her withdrawal left them in turmoil and wandering under Rake's guidance.
Tiste Edur	The Tiste Edur were a non-human Elder Race known as the Children of Shadow, the third offspring of Mother Dark, originally from Kurald Emurlahn whose Elder magic warren still served them; when that warren was shattered, Edur led by Scabandari Bloodeye and Tiste Andii led by Silchas Ruin fled to the continent later called Lether, where after a brutal war with the K'Chain Che'Malle and betrayal of their Andii allies they settled in the northwest.
Tiste Liosan	The Tiste Liosan were a non-human elder race also known as the Children of Light, second of Mother Dark's children; not one of the four Founding Races, they reached the Malazan world only after a breach in the barriers of their Warren of Kurald Thyrllan, possibly via human use of Telas and Thyr and Imass use of the Tellann.
Trell	The Trell are a non-human pastoral nomadic warrior society in transition to sedentarianism. Once a powerful and widespread people, they are characterized by their massive build and cultural ties to the earth and stone.
Wickans	Horse-nomad clans from the Wickan Plains; renowned scouts and skirmishers whose warlocks (Nil, Nether, Sormo) and commanders Coltaine and Bult make them pivotal to the Chain of Dogs.
